                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d584">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12605: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-12-30T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 30, 1933—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received December 30—4:40
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>940. Reference Legation’s telegram 931, December 21 [<hi rend="italic">26</hi>],
                    6 [<hi rend="italic">1</hi>] p.m., the Vice Consul at Foochow reports December
                    29, 3 p.m., that no further air raids have occurred; that British vessel <hi
                        rend="italic">Verity</hi> refused to allow the Nineteenth Route Army to
                    search British merchant vessel <hi rend="italic">Hatching</hi> placing armed
                    guard on board; that northward movement of troops of Nineteenth Route Army
                    apparently continues; that, according to reliable sources, troops are still
                    friendly to foreigners; and that no open break among leaders in the regime is
                    yet noticeable.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
